50|$|In 1994, Austrian {{businessman}} Reinold Geiger {{bought a}} 33% {{stake in the}} group. Through a series of capital increases, Geiger became majority shareholder in 1996. Geiger, as the new chairman, asked Baussan to return as creative director and lead product development. The company's new focus on marketing strategy {{paved the way for}} international expansion. In the late 1990s the company changed its name to 'L'Occitane en Provence', to strengthen the connection with the company's roots and because the term 'Provence' had more meaning to an international audience. On 20 April 2001, Clarins became a financial investor in the company through subscription to approximately 5.18% of the company's shares and €11,433,750 <b>convertible</b> <b>debenture</b> <b>loan.</b> On 22 February 2005, Clarins further invested €16,525,580 in <b>convertible</b> <b>debentures.</b> When the debentures were converted, Clarins held 23.33% of the shares. The management executed a leveraged buyout in May 2007 following which Reinold Geiger's stake rose from 31.9% to 48.7%, and Clarins' stake was diluted to 10.0%.|$|R
